Collision detection for rotation in a Tetris game involves checking if the new position of each block in the tetromino (the shape being rotated) would either be outside the game board or overlap with an existing block.

Let's consider a function `checkCollision()` that checks if a rotated shape would collide with the game board boundary or another block:

```cpp
bool checkCollision(vector<vector<int>> &board, vector<vector<int>> &shape, int x, int y) {
    int n = shape.size();
    int m = shape[0].size();
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        for (int j = 0; j < m; ++j) {
            // If the block is outside the game board
            if (x + i < 0 || x + i >= board.size() || y + j < 0 || y + j >= board[0].size()) {
                if (shape[i][j]) {
                    return true;
                }
            }
            // If the block overlaps with an existing block
            else if (shape[i][j] && board[x + i][y + j]) {
                return true;
            }
        }
    }
    return false;
}
```

This function takes the game board, the shape being rotated, and the position (x, y) of the shape's top-left block. It checks each block in the shape, and if the block is outside the game board or overlaps with an existing block, it returns true, indicating a collision.

When you rotate a shape, you would first use the `rotate()` function to get the new shape, then use the `checkCollision()` function to check if the new shape would collide. If `checkCollision()` returns true, you would not perform the rotation.

