Form validation is an essential part of any web application. Django provides a powerful form library that handles rendering forms as HTML, validating user-submitted data, and converting that data to native Python types. Here's how you can add form validation in Django:

1. **Define your form**: Django forms are defined as Python classes that inherit from the `Form` class or `ModelForm` class if you're dealing with model instances. Here's an example of a form for the `Post` model:

```python
from django import forms
from .models import Post

class PostForm(forms.ModelForm):
    class Meta:
        model = Post
        fields = ['title', 'content']
```

2. **Use your form in a view**: In your view, you can use the form to check if the submitted data is valid:

```python
from .forms import PostForm

def post_new(request):
    if request.method == "POST":
        form = PostForm(request.POST)
        if form.is_valid():
            post = form.save(commit=False)
            post.author = request.user
            post.save()
            return redirect('post_detail', pk=post.pk)
    else:
        form = PostForm()
    return render(request, 'blog/post_edit.html', {'form': form})
```

3. **Custom validation**: Django will automatically validate your data based on your model's field types. However, you can add custom validation to your forms by adding methods that follow the pattern `clean_<fieldname>`:

```python
class PostForm(forms.ModelForm):
    class Meta:
        model = Post
        fields = ['title', 'content']

    def clean_title(self):
        title = self.cleaned_data.get('title')
        if not title:
            raise forms.ValidationError('This field cannot be blank.')
        if len(title) < 5:
            raise forms.ValidationError('Title must be at least 5 characters long.')
        return title
```

In the `clean_title` method, `self.cleaned_data` is a dictionary that contains the cleaned data submitted in the form. With this dictionary, you can validate the data and raise a `ValidationError` if the data is not valid.

4. **Displaying form errors**: If a form fails validation, you can display the errors in your template. Django forms have an `errors` attribute which is a dictionary that maps field names to their list of errors:

```html
<form method="post">
    {% csrf_token %}
    {{ form.as_p }}
    <button type="submit
Sure, Django provides a simple and flexible way to display form validation errors in your templates.

For field-specific errors, you can access them using the `errors` attribute of a form field. Here's an example:

```html
<form method="post">
    {% csrf_token %}
    {{ form.title.label_tag }} {{ form.title }}
    {% if form.title.errors %}
        <div class="alert alert-danger">
            {{ form.title.errors }}
        </div>
    {% endif %}
    <!-- Repeat for other fields -->
    <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>
```

In this example, `form.title.errors` will display any errors associated with the `title` field.

For non-field errors, or errors associated with the form as a whole, you can access them using the `non_field_errors` method of the form:

```html
<form method="post">
    {% csrf_token %}
    {% if form.non_field_errors %}
        <div class="alert alert-danger">
            {{ form.non_field_errors }}
        </div>
    {% endif %}
    <!-- Form fields here -->
    <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>
```

These non-field errors can be added in your form's `clean` method. This method is called after all the field-specific `clean_<fieldname>` methods have been called. You can use it to check for errors that depend on multiple form fields:

```python
class PostForm(forms.ModelForm):
    class Meta:
        model = Post
        fields = ['title', 'content']

    def clean(self):
        cleaned_data = super().clean()
        title = cleaned_data.get('title')
        content = cleaned_data.get('content')

        if title and content and title == content:
            raise forms.ValidationError('Title and content cannot be identical.')
```

In this example, if the title and content are identical, a non-field error will be added to the form. This error will be displayed by the `form.non_field_errors` in the template.

